<div class="sec">
<h3 class="sectitle">Semi-Supervised Approaches to Multilingual Processing</h3>

<div class="secbody">
<p>In today's information-driven world, the ability to process data
expressed in non-English languages has become increasingly
important; therefore, advancement in multilingual processing
technologies is of great practical values.  In order to be able to
process a wide variety of input, multilingual processing systems are
typically trained using machine learning techniques rather than
hand-crafted.  Moreover, because the systems may not have access to
many multilingual resources, the learning is often
<b>unsupervised</b> rather than <b>supervised</b>; i.e., the system
must learn without outside help.  Although this approach has the
benefit that it requires minimal human intervention, its cost is that
the system may not learn as well.  This project explores applying
<b>semi-supervised</b> learning to improve multilingual processing, <i>taking
advantages of both the information of annotated data and the abundance
of unannotated data.</i></p>

<p>One focus of this project is on applying <b>cross-language projection</b> 
to rapidly build up a Chinese parser.  Another 
is on exploring ways to improve cross-language projection through
better word alignments.</p>

